WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:04.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington, DC.

00:00:23.110 --> 00:00:26.210
&gt;&gt; Good afternoon, everyone,
and thank you for being here.

00:00:26.210 --> 00:00:29.760
I'm Mary-Jane Deeb, Chief of
the African/Mid-East division.

00:00:29.760 --> 00:00:34.740
And I'm really excited
about today's program.

00:00:34.740 --> 00:00:41.900
And I always say something about
our division before we start.

00:00:41.900 --> 00:00:45.630
Because people see
the programs online,

00:00:45.630 --> 00:00:49.300 position:56%
and so if they're watching online,
they probably want to know something

00:00:49.300 --> 00:00:52.430
about who we are and what we do.

00:00:52.430 --> 00:00:59.210
So we are a division that's
made up of three sections.

00:00:59.210 --> 00:01:01.390
And those three sections
are the African section,

00:01:01.390 --> 00:01:03.820
the Hebraic section,
the Mid-East section.

00:01:03.820 --> 00:01:08.000
We're responsible for collections
from 78 different countries

00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:10.150
and at least 30 languages.

00:01:10.150 --> 00:01:15.940
We're very active in acquiring
and developing collections

00:01:15.940 --> 00:01:21.510
from sub-Saharan Africa,
North Africa, the Middle East,

00:01:21.510 --> 00:01:28.400
Central Asia, the Caucasus, and
we go as far as Afghanistan,

00:01:28.400 --> 00:01:34.170
sometimes into [inaudible]
Russia and China.

00:01:34.170 --> 00:01:37.990
And we brief visitors.

00:01:37.990 --> 00:01:41.150
We serve collections.

00:01:41.150 --> 00:01:43.770
We organize programs.

00:01:43.770 --> 00:01:49.150
And we also and we do
exhibits and displays.

00:01:49.150 --> 00:01:56.530 position:56%
We also invite scholars and experts
who have researched the collections,

00:01:56.530 --> 00:02:04.670
who have written books, who
have prepared research papers,

00:02:05.910 --> 00:02:10.430
based on our collections,
to come and talk to us.

00:02:10.430 --> 00:02:17.580
And so to help us all get a better
understanding of these collections

00:02:17.580 --> 00:02:23.850
in other countries and societies
for which we are responsible.

00:02:23.850 --> 00:02:31.230
And so in that spirit, today
we have our own, our very own,

00:02:31.230 --> 00:02:37.220
in-house poets and scholars
and writers and thinkers,

00:02:37.220 --> 00:02:43.740 position:56%
who have put together for you a very
special program for Valentine's Day.

00:02:43.740 --> 00:02:45.780
I know it's gone, but, you know,

00:02:45.780 --> 00:02:49.780
Valentine's Day is a
permanent feature, okay,

00:02:49.780 --> 00:02:53.580
and it was only two days
ago that we celebrated it.

00:02:53.580 --> 00:02:56.890
And this program has been --

00:02:56.890 --> 00:03:05.330
is under the able direction of
our grand maestro, Dr. Ann Brener,

00:03:05.330 --> 00:03:08.430
the Hebraic area specialist
in this division.

00:03:08.430 --> 00:03:14.550
She opined in a meeting,
in a divisional meeting,

00:03:14.550 --> 00:03:19.250
that it behooves our division to
celebrate the poetic traditions

00:03:19.250 --> 00:03:22.930
of the Middle East that go
back thousands of years,

00:03:22.930 --> 00:03:32.510
and that have had a major
impact on Western poetic forms.

00:03:32.510 --> 00:03:38.370
[inaudible] form of
poetry, of Southern France.

00:03:38.370 --> 00:03:40.770
Because Valentine's
Day was approaching,

00:03:40.770 --> 00:03:45.180
she suggested that we should have
love poems from the Middle East

00:03:45.180 --> 00:03:51.500
in some of the major
languages of our collections.

00:03:51.500 --> 00:03:55.740
The Mid-East collections,
the Hebraic collections.

00:03:55.740 --> 00:04:01.220
The African section also has
its own series of poetry,

00:04:01.220 --> 00:04:05.340
which we call conversations
with African Poets and Writers.

00:04:05.340 --> 00:04:09.870
But the other two sections do
not necessarily have a series.

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:14.220
So this is a way of
celebrating their collections.

00:04:14.220 --> 00:04:19.010
The idea was immediately
endorsed unanimously.

00:04:19.010 --> 00:04:21.640
And today we have a treat for you.

00:04:21.640 --> 00:04:28.080
With, from the Hebraic section,
Ann Brener and Sharon Horowitz,

00:04:28.080 --> 00:04:32.880
and an adopted member of our
division, Joseph Englesberg.

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:37.820
And from the Near East section,
we have the head of the section

00:04:37.820 --> 00:04:41.390
and also Turkish specialist,
Joan Weeks.

00:04:41.390 --> 00:04:45.840
We have Muhannad Salhi,
Arab World specialist.

00:04:45.840 --> 00:04:48.810
And Hirad Dinavari, the
Persian area specialist,

00:04:48.810 --> 00:04:54.610
who will read love poems, both
in the original languages,

00:04:54.610 --> 00:04:58.220
the languages that we
collect, and in translation

00:04:58.220 --> 00:05:05.030
so that we can all understand and
fall in love with the love poems.

00:05:05.030 --> 00:05:11.510
And so we are going we'll let
the show begin with our master

00:05:11.510 --> 00:05:14.210
of ceremonies, Levon Avdoyan,

00:05:14.210 --> 00:05:17.050
who is the Armenian-Georgian
specialist in the division.

00:05:17.050 --> 00:05:20.950
And now, Levon.

00:05:23.250 --> 00:05:24.670
&gt;&gt; Levon Avdoyan: Thank
you, Mary-Jane.

00:05:24.670 --> 00:05:29.140
I suspect I have been chosen
as I don't want to call master

00:05:29.140 --> 00:05:31.250
of ceremonies, I suspect
I'm the leader

00:05:31.250 --> 00:05:33.710
of the love caravan at the moment.

00:05:33.710 --> 00:05:35.940
I was chosen because after 70,

00:05:35.940 --> 00:05:38.440
