00:06:35.150 --> 00:06:41.460
a great deal of torment in
four languages of the Hebraic

00:06:41.460 --> 00:06:43.200
and the Near East section.

00:06:43.200 --> 00:06:50.430
Now picture this as
being a wind swept desert

00:06:50.430 --> 00:06:53.350
from seventh century Arabia.

00:06:53.350 --> 00:06:59.510
And I introduce our Arab world
specialist, Dr. Muhannad Salhi.

00:06:59.510 --> 00:07:06.040
[ Applause ]

00:07:06.040 --> 00:07:07.340
&gt;&gt; Muhannad Salhi: Good
afternoon, everybody.

00:07:07.340 --> 00:07:10.060
Thank you all for coming.

00:07:10.060 --> 00:07:12.350
As the title says,
this was meant to be

00:07:12.350 --> 00:07:16.020 position:56%
on Valentine's, it's two days later.

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:19.690
And some of us are quite
a few dollars shorter.

00:07:19.690 --> 00:07:22.320
But that's all right,
that's all right.

00:07:22.320 --> 00:07:29.020
The poem that I have chosen for
you today is by Qais Al-Mulawah,

00:07:29.020 --> 00:07:35.070
whom you will probably
know as Majnun Layla.

00:07:35.070 --> 00:07:39.400
Majnun Layla, the story of
Majnun Layla, I should say,

00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:44.240
is probably the most famous
love story in Arabic literature

00:07:44.240 --> 00:07:48.640
and has indeed influenced
the entire Middle East,

00:07:48.640 --> 00:07:50.950
if not saw the entire East.

00:07:50.950 --> 00:07:56.470
The story itself is known in Arabic
literature as [foreign language]

00:07:56.470 --> 00:08:01.370
"The Virgin Love," for lack
of a better translation.

00:08:01.370 --> 00:08:05.880
And it takes on many
iterations throughout the region.

00:08:05.880 --> 00:08:10.130 position:56%
Once it is adopted by and adapted,
I should say, by Persian literature,

00:08:10.130 --> 00:08:13.980
it goes on to acquire
a mystical dimension.

00:08:13.980 --> 00:08:17.890
And it's adopted by
Azeri literature.

00:08:17.890 --> 00:08:19.800
It's adopted by Indian literature.

00:08:19.800 --> 00:08:22.370
It's adopted by Ottoman literature.

00:08:22.370 --> 00:08:26.630
And goes on to have so
many different iterations

00:08:26.630 --> 00:08:31.670
and explanations and takes on
entirely different characters.

00:08:31.670 --> 00:08:35.290
But the bare bones story really,
and we have the [inaudible]

00:08:35.290 --> 00:08:37.930
and it is mentioned
in Kitab al-Aghani,

00:08:37.930 --> 00:08:44.540
[inaudible] Kitab al-Aghani, and
Ibn Qutaybah's al-shir wal-shuara.

00:08:44.540 --> 00:08:45.920
Actually, the person
who should be speaking

00:08:45.920 --> 00:08:48.730
about this is our own Dr. Tadras
[assumed spelling] who's done a lot

00:08:48.730 --> 00:08:50.230
of research on this.

00:08:50.230 --> 00:08:53.420
But I'll try and do my best
since it's a short time

00:08:53.420 --> 00:08:55.730
that I have to speak about this.

00:08:55.730 --> 00:09:01.250
The bare bones story is we have
the suth [phonetic] named Qais ibn

00:09:01.250 --> 00:09:04.690
Al-Mulawah who is completely
infatuated

00:09:04.690 --> 00:09:07.840
by a girl named Layla Al-Aamiriya.

00:09:07.840 --> 00:09:11.510
And he is writing this
love poetry about her

00:09:11.510 --> 00:09:14.990
and he is completely
uninhibited in his love poetry.

00:09:14.990 --> 00:09:18.910
He writes and writes about her,
and he's getting bolder and bolder

00:09:18.910 --> 00:09:20.390
in that he's mentioning her name.

00:09:20.390 --> 00:09:25.460
So there's no mistaking
who he's talking about.

00:09:25.460 --> 00:09:28.160
One thing I should mention, when
he talks about, for example,

00:09:28.160 --> 00:09:31.870
communion with Layla, he's talking
about communion through verse.

00:09:31.870 --> 00:09:33.690 position:56%
This is not a physical relationship.

00:09:33.690 --> 00:09:41.010
This is purely platonic
relationship, let's call it.

00:09:41.010 --> 00:09:42.310
It's love through verse.

00:09:42.310 --> 00:09:44.870
He is completely infatuated by her.

00:09:44.870 --> 00:09:50.540
The fact that he's uninhibited,
he's going overboard, let's say,

00:09:50.540 --> 00:09:55.420 position:56%
in wooing her, and he's mentioning
her by name, scandalizes her family.

00:09:55.420 --> 00:09:57.460
I mean, the poetry
reaches her family.

00:09:57.460 --> 00:09:59.750
Her father is scandalized by this.

00:09:59.750 --> 00:10:05.360
He begins to deem him
a little bit unstable,

00:10:05.360 --> 00:10:10.060
not to say a little touched, and so
he decides to nip this in the bud

00:10:10.060 --> 00:10:12.310
and marries her off to another man.

00:10:12.310 --> 00:10:17.250
The man we are told is
named Ward Althaqafi.

00:10:17.250 --> 00:10:19.320
And Ward in Arabic means rose,

00:10:19.320 --> 00:10:22.540
because apparently the
man has a rosy complexion.

00:10:22.540 --> 00:10:30.100
And so once she is married to
this Ward Althaqafi and takes off,

00:10:30.100 --> 00:10:33.860
Qais is completely -- he loses it.

00:10:33.860 --> 00:10:35.490
He's completely lost.

00:10:35.490 --> 00:10:37.480
He takes to the desert.

00:10:37.480 --> 00:10:41.480
He's seen reciting his
poetry alone in the desert.

00:10:41.480 --> 00:10:45.670
And his family starts to leave
him food out in the wilderness

00:10:45.670 --> 00:10:47.500
so he can get something to eat.

00:10:47.500 --> 00:10:50.870 position:56%
And he's completely lost to society.

00:10:50.870 --> 00:10:55.080
Meanwhile, Layla, having
lost any hope of communion

00:10:55.080 --> 00:10:59.440
with her beloved Qais, falls ill,
she's completely heartbroken,

00:10:59.440 --> 00:11:02.980
falls ill and dies
shortly thereafter.

00:11:02.980 --> 00:11:08.060
Upon hearing this, Qais
roams around her grave.

00:11:08.060 --> 00:11:11.050 position:56%
And the last three verses attributed

00:11:11.050 --> 00:11:14.760
to Qais ibn Al-Mulawah
are apparently engraved

00:11:14.760 --> 00:11:18.370
on a stone right by her grave.

00:11:18.370 --> 00:11:21.930
So it is an entirely
tragic love story.

00:11:21.930 --> 00:11:26.550
Once it is, as I mentioned
earlier, adopted and adapted

00:11:26.550 --> 00:11:30.100
by the Persian tradition, it
requires a more mystical nature.

00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:35.320
Love for the beloved becomes a
vehicle for love for the divine.

00:11:35.320 --> 00:11:39.830
So by losing yourself, in
completely losing yourself in love

00:11:39.830 --> 00:11:44.980
for the beloved, it becomes a
stepping stone for losing yourself

00:11:44.980 --> 00:11:50.020
in the divine, in another
words, beloved with a capital B.

00:11:50.020 --> 00:11:52.120
So it is a mystical exercise.

00:11:52.120 --> 00:11:55.700
And then again, there's so many
different reiterations of this,

00:11:55.700 --> 00:11:57.110
there's so many different versions.

00:11:57.110 --> 00:12:01.570
There's one version that I was
looking at, has them both in school

00:12:01.570 --> 00:12:04.010 position:56%
and the schoolmaster is beating Qais

00:12:04.010 --> 00:12:06.210
for not paying attention
to his school work.

00:12:06.210 --> 00:12:08.360
He's paying too much
attention to Layla.

00:12:08.360 --> 00:12:12.350
And when he beats Qais, Layla
is the one that gets the scars.

00:12:12.350 --> 00:12:15.340
The Indians take it in a
completely different direction.

00:12:15.340 --> 00:12:18.580
In fact, they have Qais --

00:12:18.580 --> 00:12:23.130 position:56%
they believe the two lovers flee the
deserts of Arabia and they manage

00:12:23.130 --> 00:12:28.170
to find their way back
to India, Rajasthan,

00:12:28.170 --> 00:12:29.470
and their graves are there.

00:12:29.470 --> 00:12:33.400
And I'm told there's a fair in
India ever year where newlyweds

00:12:33.400 --> 00:12:37.560
and lovers go pay homage
to the two lovers.

00:12:37.560 --> 00:12:43.240
But back to the deserts of Arabia
and to our pour forlorn Qais.

00:12:43.240 --> 00:12:45.830
I ask that you are
forgiving and kind,

00:12:45.830 --> 00:12:47.880
I'm the one who did
this translation.

00:12:47.880 --> 00:12:53.150
And as we all know, doing poetic
translations is a patently

00:12:53.150 --> 00:12:56.010
unforgiving and unthankful task.

00:12:56.010 --> 00:12:58.320
So I will do my best.

00:12:58.320 --> 00:13:02.510
I will first read the Arabic and
then I will read the translation.

00:13:02.510 --> 00:13:38.870
[ Foreign Language ]

00:13:38.870 --> 00:13:41.630
Did you not promise me oh heart

00:13:41.630 --> 00:13:46.470
that if I foreswore the love
of Layla, you would too.

00:13:46.470 --> 00:13:48.780
I have kept my vow.

00:13:48.780 --> 00:13:53.970
So why is it that whenever
she is mentioned, you melt.

00:13:53.970 --> 00:13:58.120
And why do you now long
for Layla, after you swore

00:13:58.120 --> 00:14:01.960 position:56%
to that path you would never return.

00:14:01.960 --> 00:14:05.850
Indeed, you have returned
to her, my heart.

00:14:05.850 --> 00:14:10.540
And low, tears are shed
profusely pouring forth,

00:14:10.540 --> 00:14:14.020
foretelling that passion
is a fire ignited.

00:14:14.020 --> 00:14:18.920
And beneath fires'
embers, the heart melts.

00:14:18.920 --> 00:14:20.720
Thank you.

00:14:20.720 --> 00:14:25.330
[ Applause ]

00:14:25.330 --> 00:14:29.820
&gt;&gt; Levon Avdoyan: Well, I did
