00:14:29.820 --> 00:14:35.700
We now go to our second act,
which is a flowering courtyard

00:14:35.700 --> 00:14:38.540
in Muslim Spain and
we have Ann Brener

00:14:38.540 --> 00:14:41.790
and Sharon Horowitz
and their intern.

00:14:44.510 --> 00:14:45.810
&gt;&gt; Ann Brener: Thank you.

00:14:45.810 --> 00:14:48.800
Arabic poetry was born in
the desert, but the spread

00:14:48.800 --> 00:14:51.140
of Islam soon swept it into palaces

00:14:51.140 --> 00:14:53.360
and courtyards across
the Middle East.

00:14:53.360 --> 00:14:56.860
And it left its traces
wherever we look.

00:14:59.090 --> 00:15:01.590
Poetry was chiseled
into palace walls,

00:15:01.590 --> 00:15:04.810
as we see here in the Alhambra.

00:15:04.810 --> 00:15:07.750
Poetry was woven into
royal garments and rugs,

00:15:07.750 --> 00:15:09.920
carved in marble and stone.

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:12.370
Poetry was a prerogative of kings

00:15:12.370 --> 00:15:16.000
and poets the ornament
of courtly society.

00:15:16.000 --> 00:15:19.960
And in Andalusia, in the tiny
kingdoms of southern Spain ruled

00:15:19.960 --> 00:15:24.400
by Muslim kings and princes,
it was also eagerly adopted

00:15:24.400 --> 00:15:27.400
by Jewish poets for Hebrew poetry.

00:15:27.400 --> 00:15:31.380
These Jewish poets who lived in
cities like Granada and Cordoba

00:15:31.380 --> 00:15:36.080
in the tenth and eleventh
centuries, composed poetry based

00:15:36.080 --> 00:15:38.610
on classical Arabic models.

00:15:38.610 --> 00:15:42.480
Only they wrote their poems in
Hebrew rather than in Arabic,

00:15:42.480 --> 00:15:46.310
and they used the treasures of the
Bible and not the Koran to do so.

00:15:46.310 --> 00:15:50.610
The Hebrew Love Song, which
we present to you today,

00:15:50.610 --> 00:15:56.280 position:56%
is based on a model of Arabic poetry
that was unique to Muslim Spain.

00:15:56.280 --> 00:15:58.780
Unlike the classic
form of Arabic poetry

00:15:58.780 --> 00:16:03.020
that features one running rhyme,
the kind performed by my colleague,

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:06.600
Dr. Salhi, just now,
and very beautifully,

00:16:06.600 --> 00:16:10.570
this new poetry has a far
more intricate rhyme scheme.

00:16:10.570 --> 00:16:15.070
In Arabic, this kind of
poem was called a muwashah,

00:16:15.070 --> 00:16:18.230
or as we translated into
English, a girdle poem.

00:16:18.230 --> 00:16:21.870
A girdle or a medieval girdle
being an ornamental sash

00:16:21.870 --> 00:16:24.920
or belt studded with jewels.

00:16:24.920 --> 00:16:28.210
And just as a girdle would
be wrapped around the body

00:16:28.210 --> 00:16:32.460
of its princely wearer, so
would the girdle poem be studded

00:16:32.460 --> 00:16:36.210
with intricate set of
rhymes weaving in and out

00:16:36.210 --> 00:16:38.260 position:56%
of the poem and holding it together.

00:16:38.260 --> 00:16:40.670
And here I've made -- I know
you can't read the words,

00:16:40.670 --> 00:16:42.590
but here I've made a
diagram of the colors,

00:16:42.590 --> 00:16:45.620
so that you can see just
how intricate it is.

00:16:45.620 --> 00:16:48.180
The yellow, green,
and turquoise colors,

00:16:48.180 --> 00:16:50.080
you see how they weave
through the poem?

00:16:50.080 --> 00:16:54.320
Well, that would be the
muwashah, the girdle belt.

00:16:54.320 --> 00:16:56.290
Now, all this makes for a very --

00:16:56.290 --> 00:16:59.520
all these rhymes make
for a very musical poem.

00:16:59.520 --> 00:17:04.250
And indeed, it was usually
performed by professional musicians

00:17:04.250 --> 00:17:09.100
in courtly setting, a palace
or flowering courtyard.

00:17:09.100 --> 00:17:14.430 position:56%
Now, just like the classical Arabic
poems, the muwashah, or girdle poem,

00:17:14.430 --> 00:17:17.590
is composed in the classical
language, that is the language

00:17:17.590 --> 00:17:21.300
of the Koran, and spoken
in the male voice.

00:17:21.300 --> 00:17:26.350
Except that is for the last two
lines, and that is the kicker.

00:17:26.350 --> 00:17:29.490
For in the muwashah, the
final two lines are written

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:32.850
in colloquial Arabic, the kind
of language you would hear

00:17:32.850 --> 00:17:37.610
if you wandered out of the palace
into the bazar or marketplaces

